Author: MONEY
Vol / Page: 6
Edition:
Quote: A few words may suffice to give the reader a general idea of a station. There was the usual manager's house, with a loft for the accommodation of the hands who preferred it to the woolshed, where the sheep were shorn and the wool [7] packed in bales for transmission home. There was the stockyard, ... besides a hut or two for the shepherds about the run. There were the various out-houses, pigstyes, &c., that are the adjuncts of most dwellings of the better sort in the colonies. cp <i>homestead, outstation</i> (and run)
